This patch is intentionally not applied. It is kept only as documentation.

The FreeBSD ports tree carries a patch (see niri issue #3013) that wraps
three `if node.ty() != NodeType::Primary` checks in src/backend/tty.rs
with `#[cfg(not(target_os = "freebsd"))]`, letting non-primary DRM nodes
through to device_added/changed/removed.

That workaround existed because the drm crate's from_dev_id() was broken
on FreeBSD and could not identify card0 as the primary node. Our
patch-drm.patch fixes from_dev_id() to use devname(), so the stock
Primary filter now works correctly on FreeBSD.

If you apply this patch on top of patch-drm, niri will open both card0
and renderD128 and try to run primary-node operations on the render
node. On NVIDIA that triggers a bug in nvidia-drm's GEM VMA fault
handler and panics the kernel.

See freebsd/GUIDE.md section 6 for the full story.
